## 🍎 Food Stamp Problem

### Problem Statement
You are given `N` types of food items.  
Each food item has a **taste value** (an integer).  
You can buy at most `M` meals in total.  

However, the taste value of a food item decreases each time you buy it:
- The first time you buy a food item, you get its full taste value.
- The second time, its taste value is reduced by 1.
- The third time, reduced by 2, and so on.

Your goal is to **maximize the total taste value** by choosing which foods to buy.

---

### Input Format
- First line: Two integers `N` (number of food types) and `M` (maximum meals you can buy).
- Second line: `N` integers representing the taste values of each food item.

---

### Output Format
- A single integer: the maximum total taste value achievable.

---

### Example
**Input:**
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SOLUTION CODE:
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int N, M;
    cin >> N >> M;

    if(N <= 0 || N > 1000000){
        cout << "N too large" << endl;
        return 0;
    }

    vector<int> v(N), d(N), count(N, 0);

    for(int i=0;i<N;i++) cin >> v[i];
    for(int i=0;i<N;i++) cin >> d[i];

    int total_test = 0;

    for(int j=0;j<M;j++){
        int curr_test = 0, curr_indx = -1;

        for(int i=0;i<N;i++){
            int val = v[i] - d[i]*count[i];
            if(val > curr_test){
                curr_test = val;
                curr_indx = i;
            }
        }

        if(curr_indx == -1) break; // safety
        count[curr_indx]++;
        total_test += curr_test;
    }

    cout << total_test << endl;
}

